test_policy_justification: Contributions are only accepted if they maintain 100% test coverage https://github.com/jameslamb/doppel-cli/blob/master/.ci/test.sh

tests_documented_added_justification: The policy for adding tests is not currently documented.

warnings_fixed_justification: The project does not produce any known user-facing warnings.
warnings_strict_justification: The project does not produce any known user-facing warnings.
know_secure_design_justification: The project has a single primary developer who is not familiar with the Saltzer and Schroeder principles.
know_common_errors_justification: The primary developer is aware of some but not all of the vulnerabilities documented here.

delivery_unsigned_justification: The project is distributed via PyPi (https://pypi.org/project/doppel-cli/) and conda-forge (https://anaconda.org/conda-forge/doppel-cli). I expect but do not know for sure that the corresponding CLIs for those ('pip install' and 'conda install') check checksums that are retrieved over HTTPS.

vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: I am not aware of any security vulnerabilities related to this project.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: I don't believe that the static analysis tools used in this project look for vulnerabilities.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: I am not aware of any high severity exploitable vulnerabilities related to this project.
static_analysis_often_justification: All of the static code tools mentioned in this report are run on every commit, using continuous integration (https://github.com/jameslamb/doppel-cli/blob/master/.travis.yml).
dynamic_analysis_justification: The project has 100% unit test coverage, and is tested on occasion against a random sample of R and Python packages to catch previously-uncaught edge cases: https://github.com/jameslamb/doppel-cli/tree/master/smoke_tests
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The project is written in R and Python.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: The project includes some run-time assertions but I don't feel comfortable saying "many".
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: No exploitable vulnerabilities of any severity have been discovered with this project.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: The project uses AppVeyor (Windows) and Travis CI (Linux, Mac) for this purpose.

name: Karydia
description: Karydia is a security add-on for Kubernetes, which helps you follow good security practices by inverting insecure default settings in Kubernetes. Kubernetes default settings are not optimized for security, but rather on running out-of-the-box without complicated configuration upfront. It's easy to get a pod up and running; in the simplest case it's just one command. Unfortunately, the simple setup does not have a highly secure application in mind. Default settings are not enough!
